# Pollution is in the air

We decided we wanted to have more insights on the air pollution. We did a statistical analysis of several sources to give some useful insights into what is the current situation on air pollution in the world and what trends exist for the future.

PM2.5 refers to atmospheric particulate matter (PM) that have a diameter of less than 2.5 micrometers, which is about 3% the diameter of a human hair. We focused on this air contaminant in particular because of the clear difference between other contaminants and PM2.5

After seeing that there was a slight increase in 2014 we decided we would just analise the five most contaminant countries: Egypt, Qatar, Niger, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia. Then we would compare them with 3 big countries for reference: China, United States and India. We move these to a new table for further analisys (just the data of 2016, the latest we have).

We plot a bar chart to compare their mean exposure in 2016. We are interested in how they compare with the 3 "big" countries.

It's of great interest to compare the countries mean exposure but we need a context of the effect this exposure has on the general population. For this we have found the Disability-Adjusted Life Days per individual. This metric tells us how many days of lyfe an individual has lost. 

We plot a bar chart of this metric for each country in the new table.

%md

After analysing the data we can conclude that:

Afghanistan, Central African Republic and Guinea-Bissau don't have such a high mean exposure but have a lot of deaths.

Possible reasons: poor countries, lack of access to medical resources, etc.


Qatar and Saudi Arabia have a really high yearly mean exposure but not many deaths.

Possible reasons: rich countries with access to medical resources, etc.
